member.summary: Attempts to connect to a new In-Sight sensor. If there is an existing connection to the sensor and forceConnect is false, prompts the user whether to forcibly break the other connection.
member.param: The DNS name or IP address of the In-Sight sensor.
true will forcibly break an existing connection; false will prompt the user whether to break the connection if one already exists.

remarks.p: This method changes the display's property to , raises the event, and then returns almost immediately before the connection has been established. The display will then attempt to connect to the In-Sight sensor for up to 30 seconds, after which it will return to the state and the event will be raised again. If the connection was successful, the display's property will be true. If the connection fails, the property will indicate the reason that the connection could not be established.

After the property has returned to and the event has been raised, the event will be raised. The arguments of this event indicate whether the connection was successful and if was not, what error occurred.

The method can be called to disconnect from the In-Sight sensor. When the display control's method is called, as happens when a form containing the display is closed, the display control will automatically disconnect from an In-Sight sensor (if currently connected) by calling the method.

This method is similar in functionality to the method of the object. However, the display always connects asynchronously and it handles errors automatically whereas the Connect method of the CvsInSight provides an option to wait until the connection is completed before returning and it requires the caller to handle all error conditions. For applications developed with an In-Sight SDK license, the Connect method of the CvsInSight is an alternative way to connect to a sensor that provides more control to the application at the cost of requiring more error handling.

member.name: P:Cognex.InSight.Controls.Display.CvsInSightDisplay.AutoConnectString
member.summary: Gets or sets an auto-connection string in the format: HostName, UserName[, Password[, ForceConnect]].
member.remarks:
This property provides a simple way to connect to an In-Sight sensor while using the control in a design environment without writing any code. Application code developers may find it easier to call the method directly instead of setting this property, but either approach is acceptable. The parts of this string are the same as the parameters to the method and when this string is set to a valid host name, user name and password, the display will automatically connect to the specified In-Sight sensor using its method.
The HostName part of the string can be either the DNS name or the IP address of an In-Sight sensor.
The ForceConnect option specifies whether to break any existing connection to the sensor from another application. If not specified, it defaults to true. If false, and there is an existing connection, the user will be prompted whether to break the existing connection or not. This part of the string can be 0, 1, false or true.
If the string appears to be valid but the connection cannot be established, the display remains disconnected and no exception is thrown.

member.summary: When set, executes an editing action in the object of the display.

remarks.p: This property is intended for use in HMI design environments where it is not possible or practical to call methods of the object directly. When this property is set to the name of a property of the object that returns a or object, it will call the action's Execute method if it is enabled. Refer to the properties of the class for for the complete list of actions that are available. This property is not case-sensitive.

After setting this property to the name of an editing action, reading the property will return the name of the action if it was enabled and executed. If the action was disabled, reading the property will return null (or an empty string in COM/ActiveX environments). This makes it possible for the application to determine whether the action executed successfully or not. The property can be set to null or an empty string in order to clear it out.

For editing actions that are of type CvsActionToggle this property can be set simply to the name of the action in order to toggle the action's state, or it can be set to the name of the action followed by an equals sign (=) and a value to explicitly set the Activated state. A value of false or 0 will set the Activated state to false, and a value of true, 1 or -1 will set the Activated state to true. Any other value will result in an ArgumentException. Spaces are ignored and upper/lower case does not matter.

example.code: CvsInSightDisplay1.Action = "SaveJobAs" If CvsInSightDisplay1.Action = "SaveJobAs" Then ' The action was enabled and the Save As dialog is open Else ' The action was disabled and nothing happened End If

member.name: T:Cognex.InSight.Controls.Display.CvsInSightDisplayEdit
member.summary: Provides the editing actions for the control.

remarks.para: Most of the members of this class are properties that return a object, which provides methods and properties that allow a user interface to interact with the various editing actions of the display.

The display control will automatically enable and disable its editing actions depending on conditions such as the user's access level, what is selected in the display, the display's , whether the In-Sight sensor is online etc. Your code can determine whether a given action is currently enabled by reading its property, and you can permanently disable an action and hide any associated menu items by setting its property.

member.example:
The following example illustrates how to use the action to copy the currently selected cells (determined by the property) onto the clipboard. This code will have no effect when the Copy action is disabled, i.e. when its Enabled property is false.
cvsInSightDisplay1.Edit.Copy.Execute();

The following example illustrates how to suppress the action. When the action is suppressed, it will remain disabled regardless of the state of the display and if the display's context menu has an item associated with the action it will be hidden.
cvsInSightDisplay1.Edit.EditCellExpression.Suppressed = true;
